Answer: Here is a basic Maven `pom.xml` template for compiling a Java project:

```xml
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
  xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

    <groupId>com.example</groupId>
    <artifactId>my-java-project</artifactId>
    <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
    <packaging>jar</packaging>

    <name>My Java Project</name>
    <description>This is my Java project.</description>

    <properties>
        <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>
        <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>
        <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>
    </properties>

    <dependencies>
        <!-- Add your dependencies here -->
    </dependencies>

    <build>
        <plugins>
            <plugin>
                <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
                <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
                <version>3.8.1</version>
                <configuration>
                    <source>${maven.compiler.source}</source>
                    <target>${maven.compiler.target}</target>
                </configuration>
            </plugin>
        </plugins>
    </build>
</project>
```

The LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor is a project that involves using an Arduino board to read temperature from a temperature sensor and display it on an LCD screen. The system also uses a potentiometer to control the brightness of the LCD panel.

To set up the system, the temperature sensor, such as the DS18B20 or LM35, is connected to the Arduino board. The analog output pin of the temperature sensor is connected to the analog input pin of the Arduino, such as pin A0 [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)]. The LCD screen is connected to the Arduino board, and a potentiometer is used to control the brightness of the LCD panel. The potentiometer is connected to the LCD screen and the Arduino board, with the first pin of the potentiometer connected to the VCC pin of the Arduino board [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

To program the Arduino board, the LiquidCrystal I2C library is installed in the Arduino IDE [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)]. The code is then uploaded to the Arduino board, which reads the temperature from the temperature sensor and displays it on the LCD screen. The potentiometer is used to control the brightness of the LCD panel.

A step-by-step guide to setting up the system and programming the Arduino board can be found in various online tutorials, such as the one provided by ArduinoGetStarted [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd)]. These tutorials provide detailed instructions, code, and wiring diagrams to help users get started with the project.

To support Azure Active Directory (AAD) Single Sign-On (SSO) tokens in Apache Airflow, you'll need to configure the `azure_active_directory_oauth` backend in your Airflow configuration. Here's an example of how you can do this:

**Step 1: Install the required dependencies**

Make sure you have the `apache-airflow[azure_active_directory_oauth]` package installed. You can install it using pip:
```bash
pip install apache-airflow[azure_active_directory_oauth]
```
**Step 2: Configure the Azure Active Directory OAuth backend**

In your Airflow configuration file (usually `airflow.cfg`), add the following configuration:
```ini
[core]
azure_active_directory_oauth = {
    'client_id': 'your_client_id',
    'client_secret': 'your_client_secret',
    'tenant_id': 'your_tenant_id',
    'authorization_url': 'https://login.microsoftonline.com/{tenant_id}/oauth2/v2.0/authorize',
    'token_url': 'https://login.microsoftonline.com/{tenant_id}/oauth2/v2.0/token',
    'jwks_url': 'https://login.microsoftonline.com/{tenant_id}/discovery/v2.0/keys',
    'username_claim': 'upn',
    'email_claim': 'email'
}
```
